Predictive regressions: comparing methods

Packages & parameters

We start by loading the required packages & functions.

library(tidyverse)
library(Rcpp)
library(mvtnorm)
sourceCpp("c_functions.cpp")
source("R_functions.R")

Then, we set some default parameter values. Note: because T is reserved in R, we use TT instead.

TT <- 5            # TT = number of observations
r_x <- 0.8         # rho_x
s_x <- 1           # sigma_x
r_y <- 0.8         # rho_y
s_y <- 1           # sigma_y
a_x <- 0           # Constant in the AR process
a_y <- 0           # Constant in the AR process
cor <- 0.0         # Correlation between innovations e_y and e_x
n_sim <- 10^5      # Number of simulations 
n_points <- 10^5   # Number of discretization points in the approximation of the integral
STOP <- 10^3       # Point where the discretization stops

Testing the functions

All functions were coded both in R and C. The C versions were only faster for the autoregressive simulations. However, the matrix multiplications in the large dimensional simulations made the C (or C++ in Armadillo) code slower. Below, we test the following:

  • the function that relies on correlated bivariate AR(1) processes (in C): quad_err_C_2d
  • the function that computes the MSE based on the large covariance matrix (in R): MSE_simulation
  • the function that uses numerical integration to compute the Magnus (1990) integrals: MSE_integral

We use tictoc to compute running times.

tictoc::tic()
quad_err_C_2d(a_x, a_y, r_x, r_y, s_x, s_y, cor, TT, n_sim)
tictoc::toc()
tictoc::tic()
MSE_simulation(s_x, r_x, s_y, r_y, cor, TT, n = n_sim)
tictoc::toc()
tictoc::tic()
MSE_integral(s_x, r_x, s_y, r_y, cor, TT, n_points, STOP)
tictoc::toc()

First study

The first step is to evaluate the accuracy of the methods and quantify how long they take.
The C functions were not designed to take vectors parameter values, thus we resort to ugly loops.
This is not costly computationally because the number of iterations is small.
Nevertheless, the loop below is quite time-consuming (a few hours on a 2019 MacBook Pro).

n <- (1:50) * 200 * 1000
stop <- 100 * round(log(n))
value_AR_sim <- 0
value_S_sim <- 0
value_integral <- 0
cpu_AR_sim <- 0
cpu_S_sim <- 0
cpu_integral <- 0
for(i in 1:length(n)){
    tictoc::tic()
    value_AR_sim[i] <- quad_err_C_2d(a_x, a_y, r_x, r_y, s_x, s_y, cor, TT, n[i])
    z <- tictoc::toc()
    cpu_AR_sim[i] <- z$toc - z$tic
    
    tictoc::tic()
    value_S_sim[i] <- MSE_simulation(s_x, r_x, s_y, r_y, cor, TT, n[i])
    z <- tictoc::toc()
    cpu_S_sim[i] <- z$toc - z$tic
    
    tictoc::tic()
    value_integral[i] <- MSE_integral(s_x, r_x, s_y, r_y, cor, TT, n[i], STOP = stop[i])
    z <- tictoc::toc()
    cpu_integral[i] <- z$toc - z$tic
}

Then, we wrangle the results and plot them.
We start with the raw MSE values.

We see that Monte-Carlo simulations, as expected, yield values that oscillate a lot. The speed of convergence is proportional to \(n^{-1/2}\), so in our case, the error has an order of magnitude of \(10^{-3}\), which is what we observe.

Next, we turn to computation times.

There is almost a 10-fold different between each color!

Below, in order to save time, we discard the slowest method.

Impact of T

Next, we switch to other values of T. Its interesting to see what happens when the sample size augments.
Again, we resort to a loop.

TTT <- seq(5,100,5)
STOP <- 1500
value_AR_sim <- 0
value_integral <- 0
cpu_AR_sim <- 0
cpu_integral <- 0
for(i in 1:length(TTT)){
    tictoc::tic()
    value_AR_sim[i] <- quad_err_C_2d(a_x, a_y, r_x, r_y, s_x, s_y, cor, TTT[i], 10^6)
    z <- tictoc::toc()
    cpu_AR_sim[i] <- z$toc - z$tic

    tictoc::tic()
    value_integral[i] <- MSE_integral(s_x, r_x, s_y, r_y, cor, TTT[i], 10^6, STOP )
    z <- tictoc::toc()
    cpu_integral[i] <- z$toc - z$tic
}

Then we analyze the results.

When T increases, the MSE follows. The range of \(y\) values makes it hard to discern the difference between the two curves.

Overall, the discretized integral is 5 times faster that the MC simulations.
